38:02.155 --> 38:06.868
but I was hoping
we could have a talk.

38:08.161 --> 38:10.330
About your future.

38:10.414 --> 38:12.374
I’m so glad you brought that up,
because I’ve actually

38:12.457 --> 38:14.292
been considering
joining the priesthood.

38:14.376 --> 38:16.795
-Uh-huh. Okay.
-Or...

38:16.878 --> 38:18.547
the Space Force.

38:19.756 --> 38:22.050
Better yet, the Space Priests.

38:22.134 --> 38:23.927
Space Priests?

38:24.011 --> 38:26.805
Right. Is that-- Do you have to
go to seminary school

38:26.888 --> 38:29.516
-and aeronautics school
for that? -Uh-huh.

38:29.599 --> 38:31.435
Uh-huh. Okay. Right.

38:31.518 --> 38:33.687
Well, I wouldn’t make
any snap decisions.

38:33.770 --> 38:34.896
On that note...

38:35.981 --> 38:37.858
-Oh, my God!
-

38:38.859 --> 38:39.901
MARK:
So, who’s Jared?

39:03.842 --> 39:05.886
HENRY: Just a little bit
of sniper rifle.

39:05.969 --> 39:07.596
MARK:
So I met this girl.

39:07.679 --> 39:09.347
-Her name’s Margaret... -Wait,
wait, wait. You met a girl?

39:09.431 --> 39:10.932
Yeah.

39:11.016 --> 39:12.893
-When?
-Couple days ago.

39:12.976 --> 39:14.269
Dude, I saw you last night.

39:14.352 --> 39:15.520
-You didn’t tell me anything
about a girl. -I know.

39:15.604 --> 39:16.938
I didn’t want to make
a big deal out of it.

39:17.022 --> 39:18.273
You don’t have to
make it a big deal.

39:18.356 --> 39:19.733
-It is objectively big.
-Okay, so, the point...

39:19.816 --> 39:21.818
-It’s just, it’s not adding up.
-The-the point is that

39:21.902 --> 39:23.904
I never used to say
this kind of stuff before,

39:23.987 --> 39:26.239
but I feel
like we have a connection.

39:30.035 --> 39:32.662
I’m sorry. This is just
a continuity nightmare.

39:32.746 --> 39:34.873
Every night, it’s 6:00 p.m.,
we’re hanging out,

39:34.956 --> 39:36.875
and boom-- she disappears.

39:36.958 --> 39:38.919
Like a vampire.

39:39.002 --> 39:40.879
-Actually, that’s more like
a reverse vampire. -Okay.

39:40.962 --> 39:43.298
Which is basically just
a regular human, I mean...

39:43.381 --> 39:45.717
-O-Okay. -Okay, then if she
won’t go on a date with you,

39:45.801 --> 39:47.177
then just spend a day with her.

39:47.260 --> 39:48.678
Did that.

39:48.762 --> 39:50.639
Okay, then take her
on a stealth date.

39:50.722 --> 39:53.391
Just you two hanging out,
no big deal,

39:53.475 --> 39:56.394
and then bit by bit,
by imperceptible degrees,

39:56.478 --> 39:58.313
things get
more and more romantic.

39:59.481 --> 40:00.982
And then bam!

40:01.066 --> 40:02.400
You kiss her.

40:03.902 --> 40:06.279
I don’t think that’s the sound
effect that I would go for...

40:06.363 --> 40:08.657
-Okay, but you got to get
the kiss, though. -I know.

40:08.740 --> 40:10.200
You just have to
take her to a spot

40:10.283 --> 40:12.160
that shows
that you really get her.

40:13.245 --> 40:14.788
I mean, you do get her, right?

40:16.123 --> 40:18.041
MARGARET:
So, to be clear, this isn’t

40:18.125 --> 40:19.709
-a perfect thing?
-No, uh...

40:19.793 --> 40:21.753
I thought it could be fun
to take a break.

40:21.837 --> 40:24.089
Hmm. I feel a little
bait-and-switched here.

40:24.172 --> 40:26.091
Gonna be fun.

40:27.676 --> 40:29.261
You only live once.

40:29.344 --> 40:31.805
Oh, I see what you did there.

40:40.230 --> 40:41.773
You practiced that.

40:41.857 --> 40:44.651
-Yeah, like a million times.
-

40:44.734 --> 40:46.945
MARGARET: Um, I don’t have
great associations

40:47.028 --> 40:49.281
with this gym,
which will not be improved

40:49.364 --> 40:51.199
if some security guard
comes in here and tases us.

40:51.283 --> 40:52.993
Oh, it’s okay, I’ll just
tell him it was all my idea.

40:53.076 --> 40:55.328
This was your idea.

41:02.878 --> 41:04.379
What?

41:04.462 --> 41:06.673
BRUCE McCANDLESS II: Ah, we’re
getting a picture on the TV.

41:07.966 --> 41:09.843
BUZZ ALDRIN:
You got a good picture, huh?

41:09.926 --> 41:12.512
McCANDLESS: Uh, there’s
a great deal of contrast in it,

41:12.596 --> 41:15.724
and, uh, currently it’s
upside down on our monitor,

41:15.807 --> 41:18.310
but we can make out
a fair amount of detail.

41:25.775 --> 41:27.611
Here, we got to put these on.

41:27.694 --> 41:29.446
-Seriously?
-Seriously.

41:43.376 --> 41:44.878
McCANDLESS:
Okay, Neil, we can see you

41:44.961 --> 41:46.630
coming down the ladder now.

41:52.469 --> 41:54.095
What?!

41:54.179 --> 41:56.097
NEIL ARMSTRONG:
Okay, I just checked

41:56.181 --> 41:58.433
getting back up to
that first step, Buzz.

41:58.516 --> 42:01.895
It’s, uh... the strut isn’t
collapsed too far,

42:01.978 --> 42:04.731
but it’s adequate
to get back up.

42:04.814 --> 42:06.233
McCANDLESS:
Roger. We copy.

42:06.316 --> 42:07.651
ARMSTRONG:
Takes a pretty good little jump.

42:14.157 --> 42:17.202
That’s one small step
for Margaret...

42:17.285 --> 42:19.329
No, don’t ruin it.

42:22.958 --> 42:25.377
You know the real flag
fell over?

42:28.046 --> 42:30.674
It got knocked down
when they took off

42:30.757 --> 42:32.259
to go back to Earth.

42:34.010 --> 42:36.680
Maybe you could put it back up.

42:39.724 --> 42:41.768
Space food?

42:50.902 --> 42:52.862
What?

42:56.574 --> 42:59.494
MARGARET: Come in,
come in, come in, Mark.

43:11.464 --> 43:13.008
Why did you do this?

43:13.091 --> 43:15.385
I-I just had some time to kill.

43:15.468 --> 43:18.305
No, you didn’t. Not really.

43:18.388 --> 43:20.265
How did you do it?

43:20.348 --> 43:22.475
Well, I had a lot of practice,
for one.

43:22.559 --> 43:27.147
And then I-I may
or may not have bribed

43:27.230 --> 43:29.816
all of the kids
in the art department.

43:31.735 --> 43:35.196
I just, I wanted to, um...

43:40.660 --> 43:42.912
Uh, you know...

43:42.996 --> 43:44.831
What?

43:51.129 --> 43:53.173
There’s one more thing.

43:53.256 --> 43:55.175
What?

43:56.634 --> 43:59.095
We have to get back to Earth.

43:59.179 --> 44:01.681
-How?
-With a space shuttle.

44:01.765 --> 44:03.516
Space shuttles are suborbital;

44:03.600 --> 44:05.560
they don’t actually go
to the moon.

44:12.525 --> 44:16.112
MARK: I promise,
you will not regret this.

44:19.115 --> 44:21.409
MARGARET:
No.

44:23.370 --> 44:25.372
-Ah!

44:25.455 --> 44:27.332
-I already regret this.
-I wasn’t ready yet.

44:27.415 --> 44:29.376
-Okay.
-Okay.

44:30.960 --> 44:34.339
-

44:40.303 --> 44:42.347
MARGARET:
Oh, no, no, no!

44:42.430 --> 44:44.391
-MARGARET: Oh, my God! Ah!

44:44.474 --> 44:47.102
JACK KING: 15 seconds,
guidance is internal.

44:47.185 --> 44:50.814
-12, 11, ten, nine...
-Ah!

44:50.897 --> 44:52.982
-Ignition sequence start.

44:53.066 --> 44:54.609
Well, hang on!

44:54.692 --> 44:56.820
Six, five, four,

44:56.903 --> 45:00.490
-three, two, one, zero.
-

45:00.573 --> 45:03.618
All engines running.
Liftoff!

45:03.701 --> 45:07.163
We have a liftoff,
32 minutes past the hour.

45:07.247 --> 45:08.998
Liftoff...

45:26.558 --> 45:30.353
And you wake up at exactly
the same time every morning,

45:30.437 --> 45:33.064
except, you know,
if you stayed up all night,

45:33.148 --> 45:34.649
-you’d mess it up.
-Right.

45:34.732 --> 45:36.443
-You-you’d crash the system.
-You’d think.

45:36.526 --> 45:38.153
-Except you can’t!
-Except you can’t.

45:38.236 --> 45:40.029
Because something puts you
to bed at midnight

45:40.113 --> 45:42.240
-every night, like...
-Mm-hmm.

45:42.323 --> 45:46.286
-Ah. -It’s like you get
kidnapped by some cosmic nanny.

45:46.369 --> 45:48.455
It’s so creepy.

45:51.666 --> 45:53.626
Is there anyone home?

45:53.710 --> 45:56.921
Uh, no. My sister’s
at violin practice,

45:57.005 --> 46:00.675
and my dad has
old-person Pilates.

46:03.928 --> 46:05.722
You want a...?

46:07.557 --> 46:09.476
Why not?

46:30.914 --> 46:32.582
Are these your parents?

46:32.665 --> 46:34.250
Oh, uh, yeah.

46:34.334 --> 46:36.628
Yeah, my mom works late tonight,

46:36.711 --> 46:39.631
so I basically never see her,
which is kind of

46:39.714 --> 46:42.383
the hardest part about the...
this whole thing.

46:42.467 --> 46:44.844
-Hmm.
-My dad recently quit his job

46:44.928 --> 46:48.640
to write a not-that-interesting
story about the Civil War.

46:48.723 --> 46:50.642
What about you?

46:50.725 --> 46:52.310
What?

46:52.393 --> 46:54.103
Your parents.

46:54.187 --> 46:56.022
Old people that look like you.

46:56.105 --> 46:57.524
Yeah.

46:57.607 --> 46:59.359
-What do you want to do?
-BOY It’s evil!

46:59.442 --> 47:02.153
Don’t touch it!

47:06.032 --> 47:07.617
So, at the end,
why is Sean Connery

47:07.700 --> 47:09.244
cosplaying as a fireman?

47:09.327 --> 47:10.995
-It’s part of the mystery.
-Hmm.

47:20.797 --> 47:22.799
I have to pee.

47:24.300 --> 47:26.719
Because beer.

47:26.803 --> 47:28.888
You should probably do that
in the bathroom.

47:28.972 --> 47:30.932
Yeah.

48:01.296 --> 48:03.631
-It is completely...

48:03.715 --> 48:05.633
hopeless. Okay.

48:13.808 --> 48:16.185
Um, no. No, no, no. No. Uh...

48:16.269 --> 48:17.812
-What is this?
-No.

48:17.895 --> 48:19.772
Hmm?

48:21.024 --> 48:22.358
It’s a work in progress.

48:22.442 --> 48:24.819
You made a map of everything.

48:24.902 --> 48:27.280
-The whole day.
-All the perfect things.

48:27.363 --> 48:29.866
But you must have just done it,
like, this morning.

48:29.949 --> 48:32.118
Well, I-I draw it
pretty much every day.

48:32.201 --> 48:33.411
Wow.

48:33.494 --> 48:35.663
Boys are so weird.

48:37.790 --> 48:39.751
It’s really good.

48:41.127 --> 48:44.255
Maybe you should go
to art school.

48:44.339 --> 48:48.426
This is gonna sound stupid,
but I, uh...

48:48.509 --> 48:51.471
sometimes I think
if I stare at it long enough,

48:51.554 --> 48:55.183
I’ll find something, like a...
like a pattern.

48:55.266 --> 48:57.060
-Hmm.
-I never do.

48:57.143 --> 48:58.519
That does sound pretty stupid.

48:58.603 --> 48:59.979
Well, okay.

49:00.063 --> 49:02.815
MARGARET:
And "tree house"-- two words.

49:06.861 --> 49:09.489
MARGARET:
You made a map of us.

49:09.572 --> 49:11.658
MARK: Too bad it’s just
gonna get erased.

49:11.741 --> 49:13.868
MARGARET:
Yeah, it’s too bad.

49:30.093 --> 49:32.095
I can’t.

49:35.390 --> 49:38.184
-Oh, um, okay. Yeah, no.
-I’m sorry.

49:38.267 --> 49:40.520
I should go.

49:41.604 --> 49:42.980
Yeah, Margaret,
are you all right?

49:43.064 --> 49:44.232
Why shouldn’t I be all right?

49:44.315 --> 49:46.442
I mean, is-is this about Jared?

49:46.526 --> 49:48.319
-No. -’Cause he’s not
gonna call for, like,

49:48.403 --> 49:49.570
-another four minutes.
-Oh, my God.

49:49.654 --> 49:51.739
-Can you just let that go?
-I just feel like

49:51.823 --> 49:53.408
there’s something that you’re
not telling me, and I-I just

49:53.491 --> 49:55.201
-want to let you know that
you can. -Well, you’re wrong.

49:55.284 --> 49:56.577
Okay? So too fucking bad.

50:01.833 --> 50:05.211
Look, Mark...

50:05.294 --> 50:08.131
-We’re castaways.

50:08.214 --> 50:10.508
Except instead of an island,

50:10.591 --> 50:12.051
we’re marooned in a day.

50:12.135 --> 50:14.095
We’re stuck here together.

50:14.178 --> 50:16.764
So I just think that

50:16.848 --> 50:21.477
we need to be careful
to not mess it up.

50:21.561 --> 50:24.731
The "perfect things" thing--
that was great.

50:27.525 --> 50:29.861
But maybe that’s enough.

50:33.531 --> 50:35.658
I just think that maybe
we should be friends.

50:37.326 --> 50:39.078
And have fun with it.

50:44.000 --> 50:46.252
I don’t want to.

50:48.963 --> 50:51.299
Well, that’s all I got.

50:53.843 --> 50:56.554
So take it or leave it.

51:01.476 --> 51:04.562
Yeah, I guess I’ll take it.

51:07.356 --> 51:08.941
I’ll call you tomorrow.

51:09.025 --> 51:10.568
Today.

51:10.651 --> 51:12.737
Tomorrow.

51:34.175 --> 51:36.803
-

51:59.867 --> 52:01.619
WEATHER REPORTER
You’re going to be looking

52:01.702 --> 52:03.621
at the rain hitting ground
midnight tonight,

52:03.704 --> 52:05.498
moving in from the coast.

52:05.581 --> 52:08.376
Not expecting to have too much
in the way of wind, but...

52:08.459 --> 52:10.294
Morning, Mark.

52:17.635 --> 52:19.387
How’s Mom?

52:20.680 --> 52:24.058
She’s... fine.

52:24.141 --> 52:26.769
Good.

52:26.853 --> 52:28.980
Loser.

52:29.063 --> 52:30.857
MARK: It seemed like
she was opening up.

52:30.940 --> 52:32.900
You know? Seemed happy.

52:32.984 --> 52:35.361
Not, like, happy-happy,
but happy for Margaret.

52:35.444 --> 52:37.405
That’s rough, bro.

52:37.488 --> 52:39.323
She sounds like
an awesome person.

52:39.407 --> 52:40.700
MARK:
Mm.

52:40.783 --> 52:42.535
Nah, I’m joking.
I literally have no idea

52:42.618 --> 52:44.412
who you’re talking about.
Oh, no!

52:44.495 --> 52:45.830
-Shotgun, shotgun.
-

52:45.913 --> 52:48.875
-What am I doing?
-Not in the face. No!

52:51.794 --> 52:54.297
MARK:
Those are imperial elites.

52:54.380 --> 52:56.382
They have four arms.

52:56.465 --> 52:59.260
It’s like bringing a shotgun
to a maser fight.

52:59.343 --> 53:01.721
Well, maybe it’s better
this way, you know?

53:01.804 --> 53:03.931
Maybe you were gonna have
this doomed toxic romance.

53:04.015 --> 53:05.474
Hey, maybe you dodged a bullet.

53:05.558 --> 53:07.643
Feelings for this one you have.

53:07.727 --> 53:09.645
-MARK: Yep.
-Mmm, I’m in love with this

53:09.729 --> 53:11.480
-mystery girl, in love...
-Okay. Enough, enough.

53:11.564 --> 53:13.691
-Enough.
-Of what, exactly?

53:13.774 --> 53:15.902
This is the problem.
I thought maybe if I went around

53:15.985 --> 53:17.904
enough times, I’d get it right,
but I guess not.

53:17.987 --> 53:19.530
You know what,
maybe it is like pi.

53:19.614 --> 53:22.408
It’s just wake up,
rejection, repeat.

53:23.492 --> 53:25.202
Is that from Edge of Tomorrow?

53:25.286 --> 53:26.329
Yeah, it is.

53:29.206 --> 53:30.374
Nice.

53:34.545 --> 53:37.131
DANIEL:
Mark? Mark, is that you?

53:39.091 --> 53:40.676
Oh, hey.

53:40.760 --> 53:43.429
-I’m glad I caught you.
-

53:43.512 --> 53:45.097
Uh, I was just...

53:46.974 --> 53:49.727
I was just hoping we could
talk about your future.

53:49.810 --> 53:51.145
Chubby Hubby?

53:52.605 --> 53:54.815
Here’s the thing, Dad.

53:54.899 --> 53:56.651
I don’t have a future.

53:56.734 --> 53:59.236
You know, I’ve heard that
before from people your age,

53:59.320 --> 54:01.072
and it’s pessimistic.

54:01.155 --> 54:03.616
And frankly,
I think it’s a little glib.

54:03.699 --> 54:05.701
Well, I’m a little tired of

54:05.785 --> 54:08.454
being the only one around here
that knows what’s going on.

54:08.537 --> 54:11.666
Look, I know about the climate.

54:11.749 --> 54:13.668
I’m... I am woke.

54:13.751 --> 54:15.753
-Do not do that "okay, boomer"
thing with me. -No.

54:15.836 --> 54:17.129
That’s not...
that’s not what I mean.

54:17.213 --> 54:20.091
Bottom line...

54:20.174 --> 54:22.093
art school is expensive,

54:22.176 --> 54:25.513
and when you graduate,
what happens?

54:25.596 --> 54:26.931
I’m not gonna graduate, Dad.

54:27.014 --> 54:28.808
No one is graduating,

54:28.891 --> 54:30.977
because time is broken.

54:34.146 --> 54:35.731
Sorry, metaphorically?

54:35.815 --> 54:37.358
You have no idea what it’s like

54:37.441 --> 54:40.653
to just have your future
canceled for no reason.

54:40.736 --> 54:42.613
And don’t lecture me
about art school

54:42.697 --> 54:44.657
when you quit your job
to write some

54:44.740 --> 54:46.367
midlife crisis vanity book.

54:46.450 --> 54:48.703
I don’t think that’s
entirely fair, Mark.

54:48.786 --> 54:51.455
Why didn’t you just
dye your hair?

54:51.539 --> 54:53.791
Or, like,
take a knife skills class?

54:53.874 --> 54:58.629
Or-or just buy a Tesla, Dad.

54:58.713 --> 55:00.923
Just buy a Tesla.

55:14.562 --> 55:17.231
Could you please stop for a sec?

55:17.314 --> 55:20.192
Just a second? Emma, Emma,
could you please stop?

55:20.276 --> 55:22.653
-I-I am begging you, please.
-Okay.

55:22.737 --> 55:24.363
Okay.

55:25.823 --> 55:28.117
Thank you.

55:28.200 --> 55:30.327
-So, did you talk to Dad?
-What?

55:30.411 --> 55:33.289
He’s been stalking you all day.

55:33.372 --> 55:36.042
I may have yelled at him.

55:36.125 --> 55:37.710
You yelled at Dad?

55:40.671 --> 55:45.801
I may or may not have told him
to purchase a Tesla.

55:45.885 --> 55:47.720
Is that a euphemism?

55:47.803 --> 55:49.472
No.

55:56.520 --> 55:58.939
It’s just, when he quit
his job, I thought,

55:59.023 --> 56:01.442
"I get this.

56:01.525 --> 56:03.652
He’s doing what he wants.
He’s following his passion."

56:03.736 --> 56:05.488
And then when I try and do it,

56:05.571 --> 56:07.490
suddenly I’m lazy
and irresponsible.

56:07.573 --> 56:09.366
He didn’t quit.

56:11.118 --> 56:13.996
You know Dad got fired, right?

56:15.998 --> 56:18.167
I don’t think he messed up
or anything.

56:18.250 --> 56:21.462
They just didn’t need him
anymore.

56:21.545 --> 56:23.255
And he doesn’t want
to admit that,

56:23.339 --> 56:25.549
because he’s in
such a shame spiral.

56:25.633 --> 56:27.927
And Mom’s mad at him
for losing his job,

56:28.010 --> 56:30.179
but she doesn’t want
to admit that

56:30.262 --> 56:32.807
because it’d just
come across as too mean.

56:32.890 --> 56:36.352
They’re just stuck right now.

56:37.436 --> 56:39.355
Stuck.

56:39.438 --> 56:41.148
I don’t even think
he minds you going

56:41.232 --> 56:42.817
to that art school so much.

56:42.900 --> 56:46.028
We just can’t afford it now.

56:47.780 --> 56:49.907
How do you know all this?

56:49.990 --> 56:52.118
Psychic powers.

56:52.201 --> 56:53.536
Really?

56:53.619 --> 56:55.287
No.

56:55.371 --> 56:58.082
Because I think about
other people besides myself.

56:58.165 --> 57:00.126
You should try it sometime.

57:08.467 --> 57:10.427
Hey, Em?

57:12.847 --> 57:14.765
How’d your game go?

57:14.849 --> 57:16.392
We lost, three to nothing.

57:18.394 --> 57:20.771
I’m sorry.

57:20.855 --> 57:22.857
Yeah.

57:22.940 --> 57:24.400
Keep working on that.

57:24.483 --> 57:26.944
-

57:29.655 --> 57:31.448
-Uh, hi.
-How can I help you?

57:31.532 --> 57:34.743
Um, I’m-I’m in
your algebra class.

57:34.827 --> 57:36.579
I-I just had a quick question.

57:36.662 --> 57:38.330
I don’t think
I’ve ever seen you before.

57:38.414 --> 57:40.082
Yeah, yeah,
I’ve been sick a lot.

57:40.166 --> 57:43.210
Like, really a lot.

57:43.294 --> 57:46.922
So, suppose, theoretically,
that something happened to time.

57:47.006 --> 57:49.925
Like, the flow of time.

57:50.009 --> 57:51.844
Like, instead of going
in a straight line,

57:51.927 --> 57:53.929
like, it-it just got stuck
in a circle

57:54.013 --> 57:56.098
and-and kept repeating
over and over.

57:56.182 --> 57:57.808
-Wasn’t there a movie...
-Yeah, yeah, yeah.

57:57.892 --> 58:00.728
What I wanted to figure out
is what could cause that.

58:00.811 --> 58:03.147
I’ve been doing some research.

58:03.230 --> 58:05.524
Could the Earth have fallen
into a wormhole?

58:05.608 --> 58:06.984
What?

58:08.861 --> 58:11.280
I-I mean, I don’t think so.

58:11.363 --> 58:14.283
What if it got accelerated
past the speed of light?

58:14.366 --> 58:16.368
No.

58:16.452 --> 58:17.995
Is reality just a simulation?

58:18.078 --> 58:20.456
That is unlikely but possible.

58:20.539 --> 58:21.540
-Ancient curse?
-No.

58:21.624 --> 58:22.583
Cosmic nanny?

58:22.666 --> 58:24.376
I don’t even know
what that means.

58:24.460 --> 58:25.836
Is time just a big ball

58:25.920 --> 58:27.838
of wibbly-wobbly
timey-wimey stuff?

58:27.922 --> 58:30.424
Okay, that-that’s a quote
from Doctor Who.

58:30.507 --> 58:32.593
I really don’t remember
seeing you in my class.

58:32.676 --> 58:34.136
What if we’re in hell?

58:34.220 --> 58:36.096
Like we did something bad

58:36.180 --> 58:38.849
and now we have to live this
one day forever as punishment?

58:38.933 --> 58:41.852
This conversation is something
how I imagine hell would be.

58:41.936 --> 58:44.188
Maybe your spiritual advisor
would be

58:44.271 --> 58:46.649
-a more appropriate person...
-What about a singularity?

58:47.858 --> 58:49.735
You know, those black hole
things where physics

58:49.818 --> 58:51.111
gets all weird?

58:51.195 --> 58:52.655
Yeah, I know what
a singularity is.

58:52.738 --> 58:55.032
And, I mean, sure, in theory,

58:55.115 --> 58:58.202
a singularity could produce
a local temporal anomaly.

58:58.285 --> 59:01.163
So we would just
have to get out of it.

59:01.247 --> 59:04.875
Like, get on a plane...

59:04.959 --> 59:06.877
and fly out of it.

59:06.961 --> 59:08.879
Why not?
Now, if you’ll excuse me,

59:08.963 --> 59:11.131
I have to go do the same thing
I did yesterday

59:11.215 --> 59:14.009
and then forget about it.

59:20.266 --> 59:22.851
-

59:22.935 --> 59:24.520
Perfect thing alert.

59:29.358 --> 59:31.110
False alarm.

59:32.444 --> 59:34.280
I’m starting to think
maybe we found them all.

59:36.115 --> 59:38.242
Just had a theory that
when we found the last one,

59:38.325 --> 59:40.327
that time would start up again.

59:40.411 --> 59:41.829
I guess not.

59:41.912 --> 59:43.539
-To be honest,

59:43.622 --> 59:46.709
I’m kind of over the whole
"perfect thing" thing.

59:46.792 --> 59:49.378
You realize it’s never
gonna be Christmas?

59:49.461 --> 59:51.505
Cool. You hate Christmas.

59:51.588 --> 59:53.924
Yeah, but I don’t want
to not have it.

59:55.467 --> 59:57.469
I just feel like screaming
at everyone,

59:57.553 --> 59:59.638
"This isn’t real.
You’re asleep.

59:59.722 --> 1:00:01.265
-Wake up."
-What? Whoa.

1:00:01.348 --> 1:00:03.434
God, they’re like zombies.

1:00:03.517 --> 1:00:05.060
You’re a zombie.

1:00:05.144 --> 1:00:06.770
MARK: I’m serious, Margaret.
It’s time.

1:00:06.854 --> 1:00:08.731
Oh, no, no, no, no.
Trust me, Jason,

1:00:08.814 --> 1:00:10.858
-that’s more your thing.
-Do I know you?

1:00:10.941 --> 1:00:13.027
-Why? -Why? It’s like you said,
we’re stuck here.

1:00:13.110 --> 1:00:14.737
I didn’t mean "stuck" stuck.

1:00:14.820 --> 1:00:17.323
Everybody else is stuck.
We’re free.

1:00:17.406 --> 1:00:19.992
Free from getting older,
from going to school,

1:00:20.075 --> 1:00:22.494
-from climate change, cancer.
-Okay, great. I get it.

1:00:22.578 --> 1:00:24.538
-Pink eye. Instagram.
-What-what about all the stuff

1:00:24.621 --> 1:00:26.248
-that we don’t get to do?
-Like what?

1:00:26.332 --> 1:00:28.250
Like grow up or--
I don’t know-- be an astronaut?

1:00:28.334 --> 1:00:29.752
-Mission specialist.
-Whatever.

1:00:29.835 --> 1:00:31.712
-What about all the things
that I want to be? -

1:00:31.795 --> 1:00:33.547
We’re saying goodbye
to the rest of our lives.

1:00:33.630 --> 1:00:36.008
We will never do anything that
takes longer than 16 hours.

1:00:36.091 --> 1:00:38.010
I can get a lot done
in 16 hours.

1:00:38.093 --> 1:00:39.845
MAN:
Hello. You can’t go in there!

1:00:39.928 --> 1:00:41.847
I feel like I’m living
in an Etch A Sketch.

1:00:41.930 --> 1:00:44.016
Everything I do gets undone,
everything I fix

1:00:44.099 --> 1:00:46.518
just gets broken,
and everything that I make--

1:00:46.602 --> 1:00:49.104
-it just disappears.
-MAN: Hey.

1:00:49.188 --> 1:00:51.440
We’re thinking too small. Okay?

1:00:51.523 --> 1:00:54.026
We haven’t even snuck into a zoo
or ridden a Zamboni

1:00:54.109 --> 1:00:55.861
or ghost-ridden
any cool new whips.

1:00:55.944 --> 1:00:57.279
-Oh.
-Hey.

1:00:57.363 --> 1:00:58.906
-Public nudity...
-Margaret.

1:00:58.989 --> 1:01:00.115
-...is always an option.
-Margaret, stop.

1:01:00.199 --> 1:01:01.658
It is. I’m just saying.

1:01:01.742 --> 1:01:03.744
-Oh, thank you.
-Margaret, you’re not listening.

1:01:03.827 --> 1:01:07.247
-What?
-Margaret! Stop.

1:01:07.331 --> 1:01:09.416
This isn’t working.

1:01:10.918 --> 1:01:12.961
Is this ’cause I won’t kiss you?

1:01:14.630 --> 1:01:17.341
Why don’t you just kiss
one of them?

1:01:17.424 --> 1:01:19.385
’Cause I don’t want to.

1:01:28.435 --> 1:01:30.604
Y’all will forget
about this tomorrow.

1:01:40.322 --> 1:01:42.449
-Margaret.
-Come on.

1:01:42.533 --> 1:01:45.160
MARGARET: I have something
to make you feel better.

1:01:45.244 --> 1:01:47.162
I’ve been saving it.

1:01:47.246 --> 1:01:48.914
MARK:
Do people live here?

1:01:48.997 --> 1:01:51.834
MARGARET:
Mm-mm. It’s a show house.

1:01:51.917 --> 1:01:53.669
I guess they use it
to make people, like,

1:01:53.752 --> 1:01:55.587
want to buy one of these.

1:01:58.173 --> 1:02:00.717
Mark.

1:02:00.801 --> 1:02:02.761
It’s perfect.

1:02:02.845 --> 1:02:05.848
-

1:02:07.349 --> 1:02:09.393
Okay. Ready? Oh!

1:02:22.865 --> 1:02:23.907
Whew.

1:02:26.952 --> 1:02:29.746
You know, even before this,

1:02:29.830 --> 1:02:33.709
I always thought there was
something wrong with the world.

1:02:33.792 --> 1:02:37.671
Like, really broken.

1:02:37.754 --> 1:02:39.590
Not fixable.

1:02:40.883 --> 1:02:44.178
But nobody else saw it, so...

1:02:44.261 --> 1:02:47.014
I just walked around pretending
everything was fine.

1:02:48.182 --> 1:02:50.726
And then what happened?

1:02:50.809 --> 1:02:52.519
Nothing. I still feel like that.

1:02:52.603 --> 1:02:55.772
But with you,
I don’t have to pretend.

1:02:58.567 --> 1:03:00.569
I was talking
to my math teacher,

1:03:00.652 --> 1:03:03.780
and he said that we’re

1:03:03.864 --> 1:03:08.577
probably just in a singularity
and if we go far enough,

1:03:08.660 --> 1:03:10.954
like, on a plane...

1:03:12.039 --> 1:03:13.665
...we could get out of it.

1:03:13.749 --> 1:03:16.376
Are you really in
that much of a hurry?

1:03:17.961 --> 1:03:21.423
Like, "Hooray, it’s the future."

1:03:24.551 --> 1:03:29.431
It’s marriage counseling
and global warming

1:03:29.515 --> 1:03:32.643
and colonoscopies and...

1:03:32.726 --> 1:03:35.103
student loans.

1:03:37.356 --> 1:03:38.941
And suddenly you’re 80,

1:03:39.024 --> 1:03:40.692
and you’re waiting
for your Zoloft prescription

1:03:40.776 --> 1:03:42.903
at a Rite Aid
in your sweatpants wondering,

1:03:42.986 --> 1:03:45.197
"Where is that creeping sense
of failure coming from?"

1:03:45.280 --> 1:03:48.992
Because it all went by so fast.

1:03:49.076 --> 1:03:51.995
And you never wrote that book,
you know?

1:03:53.539 --> 1:03:56.583
Or kissed that girl or...
went to Paris.

1:03:58.418 --> 1:04:00.212
It’s all over.

1:04:00.295 --> 1:04:03.882
And it wasn’t even
what you wanted.

1:04:03.966 --> 1:04:05.842
I mean, it’s not
gonna be perfect.

1:04:05.926 --> 1:04:08.679
It’s the same stupid crap

1:04:08.762 --> 1:04:11.265
over and over again,
just like in here.

1:04:11.348 --> 1:04:14.184
Yeah, but, I mean,
you don’t actually think

1:04:14.268 --> 1:04:16.520
that this is living, do you?

1:04:16.603 --> 1:04:18.689
We’re stealing people’s lives.

1:04:18.772 --> 1:04:22.901
My dad is-is never gonna finish
his stupid Civil War novel.

1:04:22.985 --> 1:04:24.695
Henry’s never gonna finish
War Fight.

1:04:27.239 --> 1:04:31.159
my sister loses her soccer game

1:04:31.243 --> 1:04:33.912
three to nothing

1:04:33.996 --> 1:04:35.914
every day.

1:04:35.998 --> 1:04:38.500
We have all the time
in the world.

1:04:38.584 --> 1:04:40.085
No, we don’t.

1:04:40.168 --> 1:04:42.337
This is not time.
Time is the stuff that

1:04:42.421 --> 1:04:44.715
when you spend it,
you don’t get it back.

1:04:55.684 --> 1:04:57.311
Okay.

1:05:01.648 --> 1:05:03.859
Um... "okay"?

1:05:07.904 --> 1:05:11.116
Okay, there’s-there’s
a flight to Tokyo

1:05:11.199 --> 1:05:12.868
at 10:00 in the morning.

1:05:13.952 --> 1:05:16.204
Let’s go.

1:05:19.750 --> 1:05:21.501
If this works, our parents
are gonna freak out.

1:05:22.711 --> 1:05:24.046
Why Tokyo?

1:05:24.129 --> 1:05:25.881
I actually don’t think
it matters.

1:05:25.964 --> 1:05:28.175
Just so long as we cross
the international date line,

1:05:28.258 --> 1:05:30.427
it’s automatically tomorrow.

1:05:30.510 --> 1:05:32.971
Though there’s a vending machine
at the airport

1:05:33.055 --> 1:05:34.681
that sells puppies, so...

1:05:34.765 --> 1:05:36.683
I can’t afford puppies.

1:05:36.767 --> 1:05:39.811
I spent like 30 years of
my allowance on these tickets.

1:05:57.954 --> 1:05:59.623
You nervous?
’Cause I checked--

1:05:59.706 --> 1:06:02.084
this flight definitely
does not crash.

1:06:02.167 --> 1:06:04.127
Don’t jinx it.

1:06:06.338 --> 1:06:07.756
You know, if this works,
we’ll technically

1:06:07.839 --> 1:06:09.174
be saving the entire world.

1:06:10.842 --> 1:06:14.596
My sister said that I should
think about other people more,

1:06:14.680 --> 1:06:17.599
so I feel like
saving the entire planet

1:06:17.683 --> 1:06:19.142
is a pretty good start.

1:06:19.226 --> 1:06:20.852
You didn’t cure cancer, though.

1:06:20.936 --> 1:06:23.063
No.

1:06:23.146 --> 1:06:28.360
You know, when I was a kid,
I used to call these eye muffs.

1:06:31.697 --> 1:06:34.366
Although, if you think about it,

1:06:34.449 --> 1:06:36.576
an asteroid could hit
the planet tomorrow.

1:06:36.660 --> 1:06:39.705
Like, maybe that’s why
time started looping.

1:06:39.788 --> 1:06:41.623
Because it’s the last day
before the apocalypse

1:06:41.707 --> 1:06:43.375
and really,
instead of saving the world,

1:06:43.458 --> 1:06:48.171
we’re actually just
destroying it, which would...

1:06:51.133 --> 1:06:54.136
Margaret, are you okay?

1:06:57.264 --> 1:06:59.474
Flight attendants,
prepare doors for departure

1:06:59.558 --> 1:07:00.892
and cross-check.

1:07:13.238 --> 1:07:14.781
FLIGHT ATTENDANT:
Sir.

1:07:14.865 --> 1:07:16.533
Take your seat
and fasten your seat belt.

1:07:16.616 --> 1:07:18.368
-I, uh... I...
-Please take your seat, sir.

1:07:18.452 --> 1:07:19.911
-Sir, please, sir,

1:07:19.995 --> 1:07:22.247
take your seat
and fasten your seat belt.

1:09:36.840 --> 1:09:38.592
WEATHER REPORTER
You’re going to be looking

1:09:38.675 --> 1:09:40.594
at the rain hitting ground
midnight tonight,

1:09:40.677 --> 1:09:42.137
moving in from the coast.

1:09:42.220 --> 1:09:43.680
We’re not expecting
to have too much...

1:09:43.763 --> 1:09:44.723
Morning, Mark.

1:09:53.023 --> 1:09:54.566
What?

1:09:54.649 --> 1:09:57.819
Thought you were gonna
call me a loser.

1:09:59.070 --> 1:10:00.363
No.

1:10:02.324 --> 1:10:04.743
You were thinking it, though.

1:10:04.826 --> 1:10:06.411
Yeah.

1:10:10.749 --> 1:10:13.168
Hey, Dad, how’s your book going?

1:10:17.547 --> 1:10:20.175
It’s-it’s great.

1:10:20.258 --> 1:10:22.886
I mean, the scope
of the Civil War is just...

1:10:22.969 --> 1:10:24.512
you know, we can’t even
grasp it today.

1:10:24.596 --> 1:10:26.598
Do you know more Americans
died at Spotsylvania

1:10:26.681 --> 1:10:28.308
than on Omaha Beach?

1:10:31.227 --> 1:10:32.812
I... do now.

1:10:32.896 --> 1:10:34.272
As I’ve mentioned,

1:10:34.356 --> 1:10:36.691
smallpox, tuberculosis,
diphtheria--

1:10:36.775 --> 1:10:38.902
the casualties
were unimaginable.

1:10:38.985 --> 1:10:41.571
And the thing is, the war could
have ended so much earlier,

1:10:41.655 --> 1:10:43.406
especially if McClellan
had just pressed through.

1:10:43.490 --> 1:10:44.783
After Antietam...

1:10:44.866 --> 1:10:46.826
-DANIEL: Go, Emma!

1:10:50.789 --> 1:10:52.707
She’s not gonna make it.

1:10:52.791 --> 1:10:54.334
-MAN: Go, go, go, go!
-MAN 2: Go! Cover! Go!

1:11:01.967 --> 1:11:04.636
-Goal!

1:11:12.686 --> 1:11:14.562
WOMAN:
Go, Emma!

1:11:31.204 --> 1:11:33.289
I won!

1:11:33.373 --> 1:11:34.708
-I won!
-

1:12:11.119 --> 1:12:12.078
And Mark again.

1:12:12.162 --> 1:12:14.039
-72.
-That is correct.

1:12:14.122 --> 1:12:15.331
Ah. What’s got into you?

1:12:15.415 --> 1:12:17.417
-On fire today.
-

1:12:17.500 --> 1:12:19.085
Isn’t that a movie where,
like, Bill Murray’s

1:12:19.169 --> 1:12:20.211
stuck in the same day?

1:12:20.295 --> 1:12:21.671
-Groundhog Day.
-Oh!

1:12:32.515 --> 1:12:34.976
-There he is.
-Hey.

1:12:35.060 --> 1:12:37.020
-Good luck.
-

1:12:42.317 --> 1:12:45.153
-Oh! Go for it!
-

1:12:46.738 --> 1:12:48.281
You’re gonna be okay, man.

1:12:48.364 --> 1:12:50.617
This stuff happens all the time.

1:12:50.700 --> 1:12:53.661
So, was that "Tony Hawk,"
like the bird?

1:14:04.941 --> 1:14:07.402
JARED:
I’m just a phone call away.

1:14:56.826 --> 1:14:58.786
Mom.

1:15:02.999 --> 1:15:04.417
HENRY:
And just a...

1:15:04.500 --> 1:15:06.002
BOTH:
...little bit of sniper rifle.

1:15:06.085 --> 1:15:07.545
-Oh, oh, you got him on the
left? -I got him on the left.

1:15:07.629 --> 1:15:10.006
-Okay. -Okay, dude, listen.
We’re stuck in a time loop.

1:15:10.089 --> 1:15:12.926
You, me, everybody, same day’s
repeating over and over again.

1:15:13.009 --> 1:15:15.428
-What? -Like in Groundhog Day
and Edge of Tomorrow,

1:15:15.511 --> 1:15:17.222
except only me and this girl
Margaret know about it,

1:15:17.305 --> 1:15:18.848
and we were sort of almost
boyfriend and girlfriend,

1:15:18.932 --> 1:15:20.266
but not really,
and then we broke up,

1:15:20.350 --> 1:15:22.268
and you won’t remember
any of this because your brain

1:15:22.352 --> 1:15:24.270
keeps getting erased.

1:15:24.354 --> 1:15:26.147
Oh.

1:15:26.231 --> 1:15:27.815
Wait, dude,
you had a girlfriend?

1:15:27.899 --> 1:15:29.275
Not really.

1:15:29.359 --> 1:15:31.069
Well, what’s she like?

1:15:31.152 --> 1:15:33.738
She’s amazing.

1:15:33.821 --> 1:15:36.950
She told me this story about
how, when she was a little kid,

1:15:37.033 --> 1:15:38.910
she was always looking for

1:15:38.993 --> 1:15:40.203
the fourth dimension.

1:15:40.286 --> 1:15:43.456
It sounds cheesy,
but when I met her,

1:15:43.539 --> 1:15:45.625
it was kind of like I found it.

1:15:45.708 --> 1:15:47.418
There was just more
to everything

1:15:47.502 --> 1:15:49.796
than I’d ever seen before.

1:15:49.879 --> 1:15:52.548
And there was more to me, too.

1:15:52.632 --> 1:15:56.344
And there always had been.
I just never...

1:15:56.427 --> 1:16:01.015
realized it
until Margaret showed it to me.

1:16:01.099 --> 1:16:03.851
Nah, bro, she sounds amazing.

1:16:03.935 --> 1:16:06.771
Oh, no, no, no, no,
no, no, no, no.

1:16:10.400 --> 1:16:12.443
Well, if you’re all
fourth-dimensional now,

1:16:12.527 --> 1:16:14.237
how come she dumped you?

1:16:14.320 --> 1:16:16.614
That’s the thing-- I thought
everything was perfect,

1:16:16.698 --> 1:16:19.867
but there was more to the story
than that.

1:16:21.828 --> 1:16:26.165
I thought it was a love story
and I was the hero, but...

1:16:26.249 --> 1:16:28.418
wasn’t about me.

1:16:28.501 --> 1:16:30.503
It wasn’t my story at all.

1:16:35.174 --> 1:16:37.302
It was Margaret’s.

1:17:07.415 --> 1:17:09.500
MARGARET’S MOM:
What are you thinking about?

1:17:12.045 --> 1:17:14.756
Just this boy.

1:17:19.218 --> 1:17:21.346
I messed that up.

1:17:21.429 --> 1:17:23.890
It’s never too late.

1:17:23.973 --> 1:17:26.726
I mean, unless you’re dying
of cancer,

1:17:26.809 --> 1:17:28.770
but not until then.

1:17:36.361 --> 1:17:39.113
MARGARET:
You know, even before this,

1:17:39.197 --> 1:17:42.867
I always thought there was
something wrong with the world.

1:17:42.950 --> 1:17:44.827
Like, really broken.

1:17:48.414 --> 1:17:50.666
You know, not fixable.

1:17:50.750 --> 1:17:52.710
But nobody else could see it.

1:17:54.337 --> 1:17:57.423
So I just walked around
pretending everything was fine.

1:19:35.354 --> 1:19:37.106
Are you Henry?

1:19:38.566 --> 1:19:40.526
I think I can help you.

1:19:40.610 --> 1:19:42.236
-So, you’re a friend of Mark’s?
-Yes!

1:19:43.571 --> 1:19:45.323
Yep.

1:19:45.406 --> 1:19:47.200
That’s funny, because
he never mentioned you.

1:19:48.534 --> 1:19:49.911
Where did you two meet?

1:19:49.994 --> 1:19:51.245
Uh, temporal anomaly.

1:19:53.539 --> 1:19:56.000
Cool. Cool.

1:19:56.083 --> 1:19:58.878
So, if we’re in
a temporal anomaly,

1:19:58.961 --> 1:20:00.880
how many times have we had
this conversation?

1:20:00.963 --> 1:20:03.674
First time.

1:20:03.758 --> 1:20:05.301
Right.

1:20:05.384 --> 1:20:07.428
Okay, so, and...

1:20:07.512 --> 1:20:09.597
what are you doing here?

1:20:09.680 --> 1:20:12.517
MARGARET:
I’m saving your ass, obviously.

1:20:12.600 --> 1:20:13.935
HENRY:
And the dog?

1:20:14.018 --> 1:20:15.186
Oh, that’s not my dog.

1:20:15.269 --> 1:20:16.812
His name’s Chewbarka.

1:20:16.896 --> 1:20:18.814
There’s these posters for him
all over town.

1:20:18.898 --> 1:20:21.859
I think he jumped out of a van
on the way to the vet,

1:20:21.943 --> 1:20:24.237
and I’ve been looking
for him forever.

1:20:24.320 --> 1:20:29.325
And then suddenly,
there he was, just like that.

1:20:29.408 --> 1:20:31.786
But it doesn’t matter.

1:20:31.869 --> 1:20:37.416
Because tomorrow, he’ll just
be lost all over again.

1:20:37.500 --> 1:20:40.670
Mark was right-- everything
we fix just gets broken again.

1:20:42.547 --> 1:20:45.299
Okay, so, I don’t understand
what you’re saying...

1:20:45.383 --> 1:20:46.926
Wait. Did you use the shotgun?

1:20:47.009 --> 1:20:48.803
Yeah, you need the grenade
launcher attachment, though.

1:20:48.886 --> 1:20:50.555
-There’s a grenade launcher?
-Yeah.

1:20:52.557 --> 1:20:54.642
-It launches grenades.
-

1:20:54.725 --> 1:20:56.602
Boom!

1:21:00.106 --> 1:21:02.775
I’ve died so many times
doing that.

1:21:02.858 --> 1:21:06.153
Yeah, that’s the thing.

1:21:06.237 --> 1:21:08.573
Death, it’s so terrible.

1:21:08.656 --> 1:21:11.742
So terrible to lose someone.

1:21:11.826 --> 1:21:13.995
And if you don’t face it,

1:21:14.078 --> 1:21:16.247
if you don’t deal with it,
then...

1:21:18.082 --> 1:21:20.543
...you just end up
losing yourself, too.

1:21:22.003 --> 1:21:24.338
Are we still talking
about War Fight?

1:21:26.882 --> 1:21:29.051
Yeah.

1:21:29.135 --> 1:21:31.345
Yeah, you can take it from here.

1:21:37.476 --> 1:21:39.270
HENRY:
Oh, my God.

1:21:39.353 --> 1:21:42.064
It’s the key.

1:21:44.442 --> 1:21:46.402
Whoa, it’s the map.

1:21:47.945 --> 1:21:50.156
I was so lost before,

1:21:50.239 --> 1:21:52.325
but it all makes sense now.

1:21:52.408 --> 1:21:54.535
MARGARET:
Oh, no.

1:21:57.371 --> 1:21:59.415
What?

1:21:59.498 --> 1:22:01.959
It’s something...

1:22:02.043 --> 1:22:04.003
It’s something Mark said.

1:22:08.716 --> 1:22:11.177
I think Mark might have been
right about something.

1:22:11.260 --> 1:22:12.553
That doesn’t sound like Mark.

1:22:12.637 --> 1:22:15.014
No.

1:22:15.097 --> 1:22:16.682
Sorry, I think I have to go.

1:22:16.766 --> 1:22:18.476
-I have to go check something.
-Wait.

1:22:18.559 --> 1:22:19.810
-What?
-Watch Chewbarka.

1:22:19.894 --> 1:22:22.563
eat me last

1:22:22.647 --> 1:22:24.398
I love you.

1:22:25.775 --> 1:22:27.693
-What?

1:22:30.446 --> 1:22:33.658
MARK: Sometimes I feel like,
if I stare at it long enough,

1:22:33.741 --> 1:22:37.328
something will happen, like,
a-almost a pattern or something.

1:22:52.134 --> 1:22:56.681
has changed

1:23:09.193 --> 1:23:11.153
-

1:23:17.535 --> 1:23:21.539
eat me last

1:23:21.622 --> 1:23:25.334
in high contrast

1:23:45.438 --> 1:23:47.982
There’s something missing.

1:23:49.942 --> 1:23:51.986
And it’s time.

1:23:53.195 --> 1:23:54.447
Time.

1:24:36.071 --> 1:24:39.700
eat me last

1:24:39.784 --> 1:24:41.994
in high contrast

1:24:42.077 --> 1:24:43.996
No way.

1:24:53.464 --> 1:24:55.716
There’s one missing.

1:25:01.514 --> 1:25:06.811
has changed...

1:25:10.064 --> 1:25:12.691
Seven...

1:25:22.076 --> 1:25:24.829
7:00 at the pool.

1:25:27.081 --> 1:25:29.208
Pool.

1:25:33.420 --> 1:25:36.298
-MARGARET: You’re up.
-MARGARET’S MOM: Mm.

1:25:36.382 --> 1:25:38.801
MARGARET:
Are you okay?

1:25:38.884 --> 1:25:41.679
It’s a relative term.

1:25:45.933 --> 1:25:48.727
I thought we’d have
so much more time.

1:25:48.811 --> 1:25:50.354
I know.

1:25:50.437 --> 1:25:53.190
But you will be all right.

1:25:57.528 --> 1:25:59.488
I don’t know.

1:26:01.115 --> 1:26:03.909
I don’t know if I can do this.

1:26:03.993 --> 1:26:05.452
MARGARET’S MOM:
Listen to me,

1:26:05.536 --> 1:26:10.958
because I’m old
and I know things.

1:26:11.041 --> 1:26:13.085
It’s true that
we’re losing time every day,

1:26:13.168 --> 1:26:14.420
all the time,

1:26:14.503 --> 1:26:16.213
until one day it’s all gone.

1:26:17.298 --> 1:26:18.716
But you’re gaining it, too.

1:26:19.800 --> 1:26:21.260
Every second,

1:26:21.343 --> 1:26:24.597
perfect moments,
one after the other,

1:26:24.680 --> 1:26:27.474
until, by the end,
you have your whole life.

1:26:29.184 --> 1:26:31.478
You have everything.

1:26:31.562 --> 1:26:34.481
And it costs you everything.

1:26:35.524 --> 1:26:37.484
But it’s worth it.

1:26:40.112 --> 1:26:43.532
I promise that it’s worth it.

1:26:54.043 --> 1:26:55.628
You’re still here.

1:27:01.550 --> 1:27:03.093
Uh...

1:27:34.458 --> 1:27:37.628
The plane thing didn’t work.

1:27:41.340 --> 1:27:43.634
You were right
about the map, though.

1:27:43.717 --> 1:27:45.344
There is a pattern.

1:27:45.427 --> 1:27:48.138
It’s just not finished yet.

1:27:48.222 --> 1:27:50.099
There’s one more perfect moment.

1:27:50.182 --> 1:27:51.475
Right.

1:27:53.102 --> 1:27:55.270
I will keep a lookout.

1:27:56.647 --> 1:27:58.732
MARGARET: I’m serious.
I think that there’s one more

1:27:58.816 --> 1:28:00.192
and that’s the key,

1:28:00.275 --> 1:28:02.027
and once we find it, that’s it.

1:28:02.111 --> 1:28:03.278
-It’s all over.
-

1:28:03.362 --> 1:28:06.031
Margaret, I...

1:28:06.115 --> 1:28:08.242
saw you go to the hospital.

1:28:12.162 --> 1:28:15.082
I’m...

1:28:15.165 --> 1:28:17.459
not gonna...

1:28:17.543 --> 1:28:20.045
try and take you away from her.

1:28:20.129 --> 1:28:22.047
I can’t do that.

1:28:32.891 --> 1:28:35.227
Before this all happened,
I went to go see her,

1:28:35.310 --> 1:28:38.063
and they told me that
it was her time,

1:28:38.147 --> 1:28:40.441
that it was over.

1:28:40.524 --> 1:28:43.277
And that night, all I could
think about was that

1:28:43.360 --> 1:28:45.446
tomorrow can’t come yet;
I’m not ready.

1:28:45.529 --> 1:28:47.865
I’m not ready to not have a mom.

1:28:51.493 --> 1:28:54.079
I just wanted time to stop.

1:28:58.625 --> 1:29:01.795
And it worked.

1:29:01.879 --> 1:29:03.505
Mm-hmm.

1:29:07.384 --> 1:29:09.762
-Yeah.
-

1:29:11.472 --> 1:29:14.183
And I was so happy about it.

1:29:14.266 --> 1:29:17.311
I just wanted to stay
in that moment, you know?

1:29:19.354 --> 1:29:21.482
And then the really weird thing
was that you showed up,

1:29:21.565 --> 1:29:23.317
and I didn’t know
where you came from

1:29:23.400 --> 1:29:25.569
and why it was you, and...

1:29:25.652 --> 1:29:28.697
and, um, now I think I know why.

1:29:28.781 --> 1:29:32.159
I think it’s because, you know,
when it’s time to go,

1:29:32.242 --> 1:29:34.411
I wouldn’t have to go alone.

1:29:37.039 --> 1:29:38.415
Okay.

1:29:39.833 --> 1:29:41.877
And it’s time.

1:29:43.420 --> 1:29:45.380
And it’s not gonna be perfect.

1:29:45.464 --> 1:29:47.925
You know, we’re never gonna
find the fourth dimension

1:29:48.008 --> 1:29:50.469
or cure cancer or fix the world.

1:29:50.552 --> 1:29:53.430
The point is,
is that I was wrong.

1:29:56.683 --> 1:29:58.602
We’re the ones sleeping.

1:29:58.685 --> 1:30:02.022
Everyone else is awake,
and it’s just us dreaming.

1:30:03.315 --> 1:30:05.818
I know it’s gonna hurt
really bad...

1:30:07.653 --> 1:30:09.947
...but I think that
I have to wake up now.

1:30:13.283 --> 1:30:16.036
I think that this is the moment.

1:30:16.120 --> 1:30:17.955
Right now.

1:30:18.038 --> 1:30:19.998
And I don’t want to miss it.

1:30:28.590 --> 1:30:30.717
That was kind of perfect.

1:30:32.219 --> 1:30:33.971
There was a hair in my mouth.

1:30:37.766 --> 1:30:39.726
Kiss me again?

1:31:42.664 --> 1:31:44.833
Goodbye, Mom.

1:32:11.526 --> 1:32:13.737
MARK:
You ready?

1:32:15.489 --> 1:32:17.074
MARGARET
I don’t know.

